No problem. ss is just a socket-inspection tool; netstat shows similar socket information and supports the flags you need here: -t for TCP, -u for UDP, -l for listening sockets, -n for numeric addresses/ports, and -p for the owning program/PID. The Linux man page also notes that ss is the newer replacement for netstat, but netstat is still fine for this check.  ￼

Run these on the E320 instead:

which netstat
netstat -ltnp | grep 49601
netstat -lunp | grep 49600
netstat -anp  | grep -E '49600|49601'

How to read that:

* if you see 127.0.0.1:49601, the RPC side is loopback-only
* if you see 0.0.0.0:49601, it is listening on all IPv4 interfaces
* if you see 192.168.10.2:49601, it is explicitly bound to sfp0
* same idea for UDP discovery on 49600  ￼

If netstat is missing too, use these fallbacks:

busybox netstat -an | grep -E '49600|49601'
cat /proc/net/tcp /proc/net/tcp6 /proc/net/udp /proc/net/udp6 | grep -iE 'C1C0|C1C1'
ps aux | grep -E 'usrp_hwd|mpm|python'

49600 in hex is C1C0, and 49601 is C1C1, so those /proc/net/* greps are checking the same two ports.

